    treatment_brief:
      '<p>The Bone Cancer Treatment in India costs around 7200 USD which is around one-fourth of the cost offered in other developed countries including the USA, UK, etc. It&nbsp;can develop in any bone of the body and destroy tissues as well.&nbsp; This type of cancer is rare, but it mostly affects the pelvis and bones in the arms and legs. Like other cancers, it can spread to distant organs as well such as lungs, intestines, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two main types of bone cancers &ndash; primary and secondary. In primary bone cancer, abnormal mutations develop in the bones, while secondary bone cancer arises somewhere else, spreads or metastasizes to the nearby or distant bones.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bone cancers account for less than 1% of all other cancers. Secondary bone cancer is more common than primary bone cancer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What Are The Symptoms of Bone Cancer?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Nagging and persistent pain in the affected areas is the most common symptoms of bone cancer. Over time, the pain becomes worse and remain constant:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other symptoms include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Unexplained weight loss</li>\r\n\t<li>Weak bones that tend to get fractured</li>\r\n\t<li>Swollen affected area</li>\r\n\t<li>Lump formation in the affected area</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Types of Bone Cancers, Diagnosis and Treatments <a href="http://way2lab.com">(WAY2LAB)</a></strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Bone cancer is broadly classified into two main categories: primary bone cancers and secondary bone cancers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Primary Bone Cancers:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bone tumors are either benign or malignant. Benign tumors do not grow towards other organs, while malignant tumors are aggressive and capable of growing and spreading.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Types</strong><strong>Examples</strong>Benign TumorsOsteoma, Osteoid Osteoma, Osteochondroma, Aneurysmal Bone Cyst, Fibrous Dysplasia of the Bone, EnchondromaMalignant TumorsEwing&rsquo;s Sarcoma, Osteosarcoma, Chordoma, Fibrosarcoma, Chondrosarcoma, and other sarcomas</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most common types of bone cancers are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Osteosarcoma:&nbsp;</strong>It is the most common type of bone cancer which usually occurs in children and younger adults. It arises in the large bones of the legs and arms. In rare cases, the tumor can arise outside of bones (extraskeletal osteosarcomas).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Ewing&rsquo;s Sarcoma:&nbsp;</strong>The tumor usually occurs in the pelvis, legs, or arms. It usually hits children and younger adults.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Chondrosarcoma:&nbsp;</strong>It is also one of the common types of bone cancer in which the cancerous cells release in cartilage. It develops in the pelvis, legs, or arms and hits middle-aged and older adults.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Secondary Bone Cancers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the most common type of bone cancers that occur in adults only. It develops when cancer starts reaching bones from any other organs. There are higher chances that cancer can spread to the bones. Breast and&nbsp;<a href="https://medsurgeindia.com/cost/prostate-cancer-surgical-cost-in-india/">prostate cancer</a>&nbsp;have higher chances of developing bone cancer and this process is called bone metastases.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Bone Cancer Staging and Grading</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Like every tumor, bone cancer has different stages as well as based on which doctors perform the appropriate treatment.&nbsp;The process &lsquo;Grading&rsquo; involves examining the tumor cells under a microscope and concluding how they differ from the healthy bone tissues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Grade 1 tumor cells have a similar resemblance to bone tissue, while grade 3 tumor cells are abnormal and quite aggressive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stage I:&nbsp;</strong>It is the treatment stage of bone cancer as the tumor measures around eight centimeters and has not exceeded its origin limits.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stage II:&nbsp;</strong>In stage II, the tumor size may be the same as stage I, but with a higher grade and aggressive nature.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stage III:&nbsp;</strong>The tumor has developed in at least two places in the same bone. However, it has not spread to the lungs or lymph nodes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stage IV:&nbsp;</strong>This is the advanced and last stage of bone cancer which is highly aggressive. The tumor cells might have spread to different locations including lungs, lymph nodes, or other organs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the different stages of bone cancer that requires a different combination of treatments and dictate different outlook.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Departments and Specialities That Treat Bone Cancer</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Bone Cancer treatment involves specialists from different medical departments and they include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Medical Oncology</li>\r\n\t<li>Cancer Care Department</li>\r\n\t<li>Orthopedic Oncology</li>\r\n\t<li>Orthopedic Surgery</li>\r\n\t<li>Pediatric Hematology/Oncology</li>\r\n\t<li>Proton Beam Therapy Program</li>\r\n\t<li>Radiation Oncology</li>\r\n\t<li>Rehabilitation Program</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',
    treatment_doctors: "",
    treatment_faqs:
      "<h3><strong>Can bone cancer be cured completely?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In most cases, bone cancer is easily curable if it hasn&rsquo;t spread. Around 6 in every 10 people diagnosed with bone cancer live for at least five years from the time of their diagnosis. Most often, it may be cured completely.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What is the survival rate of bone cancer?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The survival rate of bone cancer varies according to which extent it has spread. If it is localized, the survival rate is around 91%. If it has spread to nearby tissues or organs, the survival rate is approximately 75%. If it has affected distant organs, the survival rate is quite less which is 22%.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Where does bone cancer usually start?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>It can develop in any bone in the body, however, it mostly affects the pelvis or long bones in the arms or legs.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How long does it take to recover from bone cancer surgery?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In the case of a tumor in the leg bone, people start walking again three to six months after a leg amputation, while it takes around a year for complete recovery after limb-salvage surgery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>How long is chemo for bone cancer?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The chemo sessions are done for about 10 weeks before undergoing surgery to treat osteosarcomas. This helps make surgery easier.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>What bone cancer patients should eat?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The diet should be rich in protein such as milk products, eggs, legumes, meat, fish, beans, and poultry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Does bone cancer show up on X-rays?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>X-rays can tell any damage to the bones due to cancer or if there is any new bone growing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n",
