      "<p>CyberKnife is an exact, painless, and noninvasive radiation therapy which could be a substitute for radiotherapy or to open operation in some specific scenarios.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout the Cyberknife radiosurgery process, the tumor receives a cumulative dose of radiation to either restrain or destroy the tumor cells while radiation exposure to surrounding tissue is minimized. The Cyberknife can compensate for patient movement to guarantee highly precise delivery of radiation during therapy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When patient motion happens during therapy, the cameras detect the position shift, along with the robot can compensate for the motion by hammering the LINAC before administering the radiation beam. This practice of correcting for beam replacement guarantees true tumor targeting.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Understanding the Mechanism</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The exceptional mechanism of this Cyberknife supplies a noninvasive, surgical-like result for lesions of the spine and brain. It&rsquo;s the first and only industrial use of autonomous stereotactic radiosurgery for the spine and the spinal cord. Moreover, this technology has the advantage of allowing the Cyberknife platform to be utilized for radiosurgical programs away from the mind as was for staged radiosurgical procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cyberknife radiosurgery has also been effectively utilized to treat chosen lung malignancies. The combo of both investigational hardware and software using Cyberknife technology can provide conformal radiation into transferring primary and metastatic lung tumors if the operation isn&rsquo;t an alternative. The Cyberknife accommodates lung and tumor movement, enabling alterations to be made in order to deliver a maximum therapeutic dose when minimizing surrounding tissue degeneration.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Cyberknife Disease Treatment</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cyberknife intervention is a superb assistance to patients that are handling deadly tumors. Cyberknife can be used to deal with:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Non-Cancerous Tumours</li>\r\n\t<li>Brain Cancer</li>\r\n\t<li>Prostate Cancer</li>\r\n\t<li>Liver Cancer</li>\r\n\t<li>Cancerous Spine Tumours</li>\r\n\t<li>Esophageal cancer</li>\r\n\t<li>Head and Neck Cancer</li>\r\n\t<li>Breast Cancer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n",
    treatment_doctors: "",
    treatment_faqs:
      "<h3><strong>Q: What is Cyberknife Radiosurgery?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Cyberknife Radiosurgery utilizes focused beams of extreme energy to destroy cancer cells and shrink or restrain the development of tumors. Radiosurgery operates by preventing targeted cells from multiplying. The aim of Radiosurgery would be to destroy the damaging cells while decreasing damage to healthy cells. Cyberknife Radiosurgery might be advocated as a substitute for surgery or in addition to surgery or alternative treatments. Additionally, it may be used to control the pain brought on by lesions.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: How long does the Cyberknife Radiosurgery usually take?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Cyberknife Radiosurgery generally lasts between 30-90 minutes. The time-span of a CyberKnife therapy session is principally determined by the number of beams used to treat the tumor and also the level of movement exhibited by the goal. Typically, tumors may be treated in three remedies, generally on consecutive times and it&rsquo;s uncommon for a remedy to extend past one week.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: Do I need Cyberknife Treatment?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Cyberknife is a somewhat new noninvasive procedure that simplifies operation and other Radiotherapies to heal tumors in any place within the body. Because it&rsquo;s noninvasive, it does not involve any blood, with hardly any recuperative time. If you would like to learn if Cyberknife therapy is ideal for you, ask your physician or phone a Cyberknife specialist.<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: How much time will it take to see results?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Many Stereotactic Body Radiation Therapy (SBRT), such as CyberKnife radiosurgery, are often delivered in 1-5 sessions and require approximately a week to finish. Bear in mind the timeframe varies between individuals and between forms of therapy. For example, neurosurgical treatments like trigeminal neuralgia will see results almost instantly.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: What are the side-effects of Cyberknife?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: The recuperative time-frame for Cyberknife is normally very little. Patients generally, experience very little to no side-effects. Some patients experience nausea and tiredness, however, the cyberknife doctor will explain all prospective side-effects prior to the beginning of the treatment.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>Q: Are there any risks associated while traveling?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: It&rsquo;s ideal to ask your physician for advice on traveling pre or post Cyberknife treatment. But, in the majority of cases, there&rsquo;s not any difficulty in flying after the treatment. We encounter a high number of individuals that travel for Cyberknife therapy in India, remain for a few weeks, and then go back to their home states with no complications.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: How is Cyberknife different from other traditional forms of Radiotherapy?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: There are quite a few similarities between Cyberknife and conventional kinds of Radiotherapy which uses beams of X-rays to ruin the DNA within tumor cells. Nonetheless, in the instance of Cyberknife, the X-ray beams are nicer and stronger. This lets them sculpt considerably more correctly into the form of their tumor. This particular skill of Cyberknife means they may be employed to destroy complicated or inaccessible tumors, which might otherwise be impossible with different kinds of Radiotherapy.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Q: Can I go for Cyberknife Treatment while undergoing Chemotherapy?</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Patients now undergoing Chemotherapy or have experienced Chemotherapy previously could be medicated with Cyberknife. It&rsquo;s necessary to say complete patient history together with a various physician before the treatment starts.</p>\r\n",
