    treatment_name: "Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) Injury",
    specilization_id: "4",
    treatment_brief:
      '<h3 style="text-align:justify"><strong><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) Injury</span></strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">An Anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) injury occurs when the ACL is stretched or torn partially or completely. ACL is the tissue connecting the thighbone to the shinbone.&nbsp; Most ACL-related injuries occur while playing sports like basketball, skiing, tennis, and football. Some of the symptoms of the injury include joint swelling, a cracking sound during injury, instability of the knee, and pain. An ACL injury cannot heal on its own due to a lack of blood supply to the damaged area, sportspersons, therefore, mostly need to opt for an ACL injury surgery. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Procedure for Treatment </strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11.0pt">During the ACL reconstruction surgery, you will be under general anaesthesia and hence will be asleep during the whole procedure. Small incisions are made by the surgeon around the knee to create entry portals for various arthroscopic and surgical instruments. Once the arthroscopy is inserted, it delivers a saline solution to create space for surgical tools including the arthroscopic camera, which sends footage to a monitor monitored by the surgeons. He or she then evaluates the structures surrounding the ACL, including the left and right meniscus and the articular cartilage. The surgeon repairs the lesions in the soft tissues, if any. A graft from another part of the patient&rsquo;s body is taken and attached to the end to plugs of bone taken from the patella and tibia. These plugs anchor the graft which will become the new ACL. The new ACL is inserted into the femur and tibia with the help of a flexible guidewire. Then, to secure the wire, screws are used. With time, these plugs grow into the surrounding bone. The surgical instruments are then removed. ACL surgery usually takes about two to two and a half hours of time. </span></p>\r\n',
    treatment_doctors: "",
    treatment_faqs:
      '<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 1. Is ACL surgery painful?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.</strong> Some patients experience discomfort and pain during the first week after the treatment. But the pain reduces with time. You should have minimal irritation after the first two weeks. Swelling and bruising are common as well but fade away with time. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 2. How soon after ACL surgery can you walk?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>2-4 weeks after the surgery the patient can walk unassisted and can expect to be able to brisk walk after 10-12 weeks.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 3. What are the risks of ACL surgery?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>Missed concomitant injuries, tunnel malposition, patellar fracture, knee stiffness, and infection are some major complications which arise after an ACL surgery.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 4. How much does an ACL surgery cost?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>An ACL surgery costs approximately 1 lakh in India.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 5. What happens if one has to wait too long to get ACL surgery?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>In that case, you will get chronic ACL deficiency and your surgeon may not be able to correct all of the joint damage. You are also at a high risk of developing chronic knee pain and instability if you delay the surgery by up to six months.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 6. How many postoperative exercises can I do?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>You can do as many as you can. Start with two to three of each at first reaching some more a few hours later. It is appropriate to do some multiple times in a day than by doing many in one go. You must listen to your body and if you feel excess pain and swelling, you should back off a bit. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Q. 7. How can I minimize scarring?</strong></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><strong>Ans.&nbsp;</strong>Use compression as much as you want to. This includes an elastic bandage wrapped from the ankle to just above the knee, elastic stockings, snug, fitting leggings, or a support hose. After the incisions have healed, apply lotion and gently massage along and across each side of the scar. Some people even suggest that the use of vitamin E can help in minimizing scars even though there is no scientific proof of this.</span></span></p>\r\n',
